HTTP Status Codes — Big Picture

They’re grouped like this:

✅ 1xx — Informational
Request received, still processing
✅ 2xx — Success
Everything worked
Code	Meaning
200	OK
201	Created
204	No Content
⚠️ 3xx — Redirection
Client needs to take another action
Code	Meaning
301	Moved Permanently
302	Found (temporary redirect)
304	Not Modified
🚫 4xx — Client Errors (IMPORTANT for your case)

👉 Problem is with the request, not the server

Code	Meaning :

400	Bad Request (invalid input)
401	Unauthorized (authentication required or failed)
403	Forbidden (you are authenticated, but not allowed)
404	Not Found
405	Method Not Allowed
408	Request Timeout
429	Too Many Requests
💥 5xx — Server Errors

👉 Problem is on the server side

Code	Meaning
500	Internal Server Error
502	Bad Gateway
503	Service Unavailable
504	Gateway Timeout
🎯 Your Scenario (401)

You said:

teammate hit URL with different parameters → got 401

👉 What 401 actually means:

Request reached server ✅
Server understood it ✅
But authentication failed or missing ❌

🔍 Common reasons for 401
Missing Authorization header
Invalid token / API key
Expired token
Wrong auth format (e.g., Bearer missing)
Endpoint requires login but request is anonymous
⚠️ Difference that confuses everyone
🔹 401 vs 403
Code	Meaning
401	"Who are you?" (not authenticated)
403	"I know you, but you’re not allowed"
